<!-- ============================================================
VOICING PLAN:
- mm. 1-5 (Phrase 1): Lighter opening — "33" triad root position
  throughout. LH: G2-D3-G3 open fifths (P4+P4). RH: 2-note dyads.
- mm. 6-10 (Phrase 2): Repeat phrase builds texture. RH broken
  arpeggios (single passing notes). LH gains a 4th note (B3) at
  stronger beats. Em uses "33" vi in both phrases.
- mm. 11-14 (Phrase 3): Climax. RH fills to 3 notes per chord;
  ascending broken D (V) arpeggio in m.11. LH uses "334"
  (triad+octave) in m.13 climax chord. Penultimate m.14 uses
  IV→I→V with 4-note LH on IV.
- m.15 (Final): Root-position I with 4-note LH and 3-note RH.
  No pedal added (lever harp range sufficient).

VOICE LEADING HIGHLIGHTS:
- mm. 2/7: Em (vi) approached by step from G (I), LH E2→G2 (M3
  upward leap, acceptable). D (V) follows Em by step in all voices.
- mm. 4/9: vii° (F#°) resolves upward by half-step in RH (F#→G),
  LH similar motion. This is the most chromatically active moment.
- m.13 climax: all 4 harmonic functions in one bar (I vi V I),
  contrary motion between hands (LH descends G→E→D→G, RH ascends).
- m.14: IV suspension — RH holds C5 across IV→I boundary; resolves
  downward to B4 on I.

TEXTURE ARC:
- mm. 1-5: 2+3 notes (light); RH dyads, LH 3-note open fifths.
- mm. 6-10: 2+3→3+4 (building); RH broken, LH gains 4th note.
- mm. 11-14: 3+4 (full); RH 3-note, LH 4-note, contrary motion.
- m.15: 3+4 (settled); root position close, final tonic.
============================================================ -->
